The historical maps of the digital Bavarian Atlas, an offer of the Bavarian Geoportal of the state government, are all other than current - but precisely for this reason very informative.
Especially if you compare them with current online maps.
Then it becomes clear how cities and municipalities in the Munich Mercury area have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bayern Atlas is a flick carpet that is not recognized as such.
For cities and municipalities, more detailed maps, so-called old position sheets, were incorporated into the large overview map.
These were created between 1810 and 1864, according to the Bavarian measurement administration, and originate from the first Bavarian measurement.
The author is Napoleon.
The French army leader occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied land and ordered a topographic recording of Bavaria - of course for military purposes.
Although the French troops eventually withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville of 9 February 1801, it was the neighbors of today who created the idea of a comprehensive Bavarian map.
Courtyard Max IV Joseph further advanced the project, establishing the "Topographical Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Survey Administration.
The Urpositionsblatt for Munich dates back to 1856 and can be found on the website of the Bavarian Landesbibliothek.
The comparison between the past and the present is the most impressive in the example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which still appears relatively isolated on the map of 1856.
Sendling was incorporated into the Munich district 21 years after the map was created, i.e. in 1877.
Today it is located in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendling are concentrated around 1856 along the present-day Plinganserstraße, named only in 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the Bavarian peasant uprising against Austria in 1705.
Where the West Park is today, you can see nothing but fields - at first glance: when you zoom in, a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers appears: handwritten numbered pieces of the so-called "original recording", from which the land tax was derived.
There are no longer farmers in small plots, but small gardeners from the "Land in Sun" plant.
A large green area stands to the north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, since 1810 the scene of the Oktoberfest, was actually still a lawn in the 19th century – not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the Urpositionsblatt, in the area of today's Au-Haidhausen district, one reads not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the height "Auf der Lüften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstraße people were once locked up with delusions.
In 1858/59 the Münchner Kreis-Irrenanstalt "Auf der Auer Lüften" was founded.
Beginning in 1872, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institution - the psychiatrist who is brought in connection with the death of King Ludwig II.
“He was progressive for his time and, for example, ended the questionnaire of the so-called fools.
In addition, he has prohibited personnel from using violence against the occupants,” says Hermann Wilhelm, head of the Haidhausen Museum, who has been engaged in an exhibition with the facility.
Initially there was room for 280 patients, but later it was expanded to 500 seats.
At some point, this capacity was also no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the district railway plant in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006 there is the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost, one of the largest psychiatric clinics in Germany.
In the area of the former Auer Anstalt, young people now meet in the Salesianum in Munich.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and turned it into a youth home with training establishments.
To the west is the TSV Munich Ost football court, to the east residential houses from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's house "Casa Don Bosco" was built - in architectural reminiscence of the original building of the Madness Institute, which had been destroyed in bombings during World War II.
The Marienplatz was listed as the "Hauptplatz" around 1856 and the Kaufingerstraße was called the "Kaufinger Gasse".
A decisive change brought the Second World War also in the heart of Munich.
The Allied bombs crushed many holes in the city centre in December 1944.
One remained to this day - at the Marienhof.
The English Institute, small business houses and a medieval tomb chapel once stood at the Marienhof, where these days the preparations and on 5 April 2017 the spatenstich for the second S-Bahn main line take place.
