Citizens’ Rights Group Releases Travel Warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Promotion of Color has issued a warning for colored people traveling to Missouri due to the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
“The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which will take effect by August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to pay special attention and extreme caution when traveling through the state as a series of questionable, race-based incidents have recently occurred across the state and are recorded here,” the group said in a statement.
A recently passed Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state’s law enforcement agencies disproportionately targeting minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
“They have violations of civil rights that happen to people.
They’re being stopped because of their skin color, they’re beaten or killed,” Missouri NAACP president Rod Chapel told Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints with such frequency that we haven't heard before."
It is the first such warning the organization has issued for a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist crimes against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year after he had no more gasoline while traveling through the state and was arrested by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The Council also points out a recent report from the Office of the Missouri Attorney General showing that black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than whites.
“The recommendation is that people be aware and inform their families, friends and employees about what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared whether they bring deposit money or let relatives know they’re traveling through the state.”
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI’s hate crime reporting program, which ranked the state 16th in the country in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after states had passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for immigration violations, which, according to the ACLU, will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel alerts are typically issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently stakeholders have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the U.S.
