Poverty and Death in Indonesia
When Bardina Degei is cooking dinner, she doesn’t use a stove.
She rarely uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai Regenthood in the turbulent Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually puts a sweet potato – locally referred to as “nota” – right into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the carbonated knot is taken with eager, unwashed hands and swallowed.
Degei sits on the clay floor — she has no furniture — where she also performs her daily work, such as washing clothes with dull water from the nearby swamp.
A bowl in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband’s four wives, no fields were assigned to her.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most villagers are unemployed, and many drink hard, and there are the soldiers here.
“No one dares to run around the village after 5 p.m.,” she says.
It is a rare insight into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was admitted to Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in Indonesia, when only 1,026 elders were to vote through a public hand lift before the occupying troops.
An existing movement that revolted for independence against Dutch rule quickly turned against the government of Jakarta, whichins control of the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers from it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea comprising the eastern part of the island.
The trip includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire and then a morning 5-hour drive by rental car.
There is no public transportation.
The city, with about 19,000 inhabitants, consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, and wooden roofs converted by rust into various yellow-brown tones.
Very few Indonesians have made their trip here, let alone journalists and virtually no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
“We weren’t used to wearing those clothes,” says Degei, pointing to her vibrant, hand-woven turban, her dark shirt, and her light coat.
“In the past, we only had leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of people living below the poverty line and having some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
It is also Indonesia’s gold country.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just 60 miles from Paniai, a New Jersey-sized highland province with 153,000 inhabitants.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion in gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated $78 billion.
However, these wealths are a source of misery for Papua, which ensures that Indonesia’s powerful militaryins a suffocating presence.
A 2005 investigation in the New York Times that Freeport paid local military personnel and units $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten these golden goats and are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papua have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua’s tribal homeland in the 1970s were classified as genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
“We’ll lose everything,” Brisbane Archdiocese’s 2016 report says, which includes reports of last year’s atrocities, such as illegal executions and torture – rape and electrocution are popular, according to another report – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims as incidents happen every week,” says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have intensified as Papua’s resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province’s population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but demographic developments change as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warung cantines sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people are fighting to stay here.
“The migrants have begun selling chickens and vegetables on the traditional market cheaper than the local Papua,” explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the provincial capital of Jayapura to work.
"It has cost the native Papua - the mom-mama [the women] of Papua - their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, pledged to address inequalities and violations of laws in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua’s 29 districts – including Paniai – on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel deceived.
“Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored,” says You.
In fact, Paniai suffered a low point only two months after Jokowi’s inauguration in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas songs in front of a camp fire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers broke through the dark on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them to turn on their lights.
