New results of Swedish asylum age assessment tests
Recent results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden who have undergone a new method of medical assessment of their age show that more than 80 percent of those tested are older than 18 years old.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) began carrying out the tests last year.
During the asylum procedure, they are to make the age assessment more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for mistakes in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has submitted 6,880 cases for testing and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were rated 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency rated that the person was “possibly 18 years or older.”
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person “possibly is under 18 years old.”
The tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past few months.
"We don't see much difference in the statistics of the past months, the figures are pretty constant," he told The Local magazine.
The high percentage of cases in which the person was judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his or her age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said there are 442 cases that “suggest that the person being examined is 18 years old or older.”
When the Svenska Dagbladet newspaper examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that he would be 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRIs of knee joints are taken, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
One skeptic is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of people to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don’t think the type of measurement should be used.
Assessing biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can’t say it for sure, we shouldn’t pretend we could,” he told Metro.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: “In general, you can say that the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is when the person is just under 18, in this case, that’s about 10 percent.”
