NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will be given access to "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September after a fight before the High Court against funding the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) taken before sexual intercourse, which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 percent, is now being delivered by the health service through a first three-year study of an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the process after the Court of Appeal confirmed a Supreme Court ruling last year that the NHS had the authority to pay for PrEP despite the claim that local authorities should fund it.
The chess move announced on Thursday was welcomed by NHS England chief Simon Stevens as an “important new intervention,” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a “decisive moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to enable people to register, and more clinics will follow in October before it will be introduced across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a consequence of HIV preparations taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that just enough drugs are present in a person’s body to prevent HIV infection.
Such medications can be taken every day or so two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender men and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics will identify suitable participants who agree to the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a general practitioner can also sign up for a possible participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The program will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week following an international competitive procurement.
The study aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how it is targeted, captured, and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: “This major new intervention should complement and surpass the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity’s biggest health challenges.”
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National Aids Trust), said: “This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted at needy and vulnerable people, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
Starting in September, people at high risk for HIV will have access to this NHS-funded experiment in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, leading to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement.”
Ian Green, Chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The priority now has to be that the study is carried out quickly across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is left behind.
Now that the PrEP test medicine has been obtained, we are on the best track to protect more than 10,000 HIV-infected people.”
Sharon Hodgson, Shadow Health Minister, said: “The start of the PrEP process is welcome and delayed after months of delays and hesitant implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and stop the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This experiment brings us a step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it is important that this study is carried out as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are infected with HIV and that it will help us get one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society.”
