Deutsche Bahn to Test Comfort Check-in
It is a moment that almost everyone has experienced: you are sitting in the train and sleeping without knowing anything.
Or you’re deeply immersed in your work and you just have a genius idea.
And then puff.
Comes the creator and wakes a foolish or tears the passenger out of the workflow in the middle.
The ticket control.
But the time of interruptions is soon over.
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing the unchecked ticket control.
You simply confirm by phone that you have taken your seat and thus devaluate the ticket.
A test operation is currently underway on two routes.
“When the offer comes, we will expand it.
It is then expected to be available at the beginning of next year on many other long-distance transport routes in Germany," a railway spokesman said.
“Comfort Check-in” means the train devaluation of tickets without Schaffner.
To be able to use it, however, a number of conditions must be met: you need a smartphone or a tablet.
And you have to have booked an online ticket – which is what most passengers already do.
You must also have purchased it via the train app, the DB Navigator, which is the most convenient way to book tickets anyway.
Finally, you need a seat reservation.
Because the “comfort check-in” works like this: you get on the train, call your ticket under “My tickets”.
In the test customers then a button for electronic devaluation appears.
Train attendants receive a message on their mobile devices that Passenger X is on the train and has taken the reserved seat Y.
If the train attendant comes to place Y at the ticket check, he knows that there is a passenger sitting there with an online ticket already devalued.
So you can continue to sleep, continue to work, keep silent.
The "check-in" has two advantages: one for the customer, one for the train - which in turn is intended to benefit the passengers.
"Whoever wants to travel relaxedly without ticket control through our train staff, simply check in in the DB Navigator yourself.
This allows passengers to personalize their time on the train,” says Michael Peterson, Marketing Board of DB Distance Transport.
Second plus: “And our employees have more time than today to address the individual customer needs.”
Those who frequently ride trains know that in addition to delays and missed trains, ticket checks are among the biggest annoyances.
Because often you yourself, but in any case one of the fellow travellers does not have all the documents you need to devalue online tickets.
Either the credit card or identity card or any other document that must be presented is missing.
The result is endless discussions between train attendants and passengers, which leads to poor mood in the department or large space and delays in checking your own ticket and ultimately takes the creator time to take care of other matters.
Only a small number of customers can still use the new service.
And that only on the connections ICE 915 Dortmund-Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart-Essen.
Other trains on the same route have not yet been unlocked.
How did an activist learn the answer to the question: “Who’s the streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just a day after she arrived in New York City, the St. Louis-born was sitting on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled over a post from someone from high school.
“The police just killed an 18-year-old boy, and he’s still lying on the street,” it said.
Confused as no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on their timeline.
The St. Louis area rapper was about to live tweet the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old who was killed by a white policeman in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown’s lifeless body stretched out on the street and would stay there for four hours.
“That’s wild,” Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new for them and their community.
She laid off her phone to return to tweets about people on the Canfield drive later in the evening.
There were photos of police gangs and people screaming, and of a man claiming to be Brown’s father, who carried a sign with the inscription: “Ferguson’s police just killed my unarmed son!”
She watched a live feed in which a police officer stood in front of a group of protesters with a beating dog.
In another video, she said, another policeman seized his gun and shouted, “I’ll kill you... animals all.”
“That’s not usual,” Ferrell recalled her statement.
“That’s not the kind of murder we’ve become accustomed to and we can call typical.”
At that moment I felt frost.
I was angry and crying.”
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 23 o'clock, she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, “Who’s Streets?” in theaters from the 11th.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience, consisting of the viewpoint of people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who was wearing a flower dress and a suitable crown, the two discussed a conversation they had countless times before that morning “about the black experience and the black state.”
"Do you remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she recalled what she said.
“We’re going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that wasn’t right.
I couldn’t take them with me,” Ferrell said later.
“What happened today is the culmination of what happened in the past.
She must know it and see it and be raised in it.
It must be well developed, knowing not only activism and organization, but also the different layers of black experience and black constitution, and what we need to do to become free, to free ourselves.
Even though I’m lucky enough to give her an experience where she personally doesn’t experience flagrant racism, she’s no different than the next black woman’s child.
I feel like I’d do her a bad service to keep her away from it.”
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place opposite the police station that became a campsite as activists waited for possible non-accusation of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and her daughter joined up with a local business owner who was making lunch.
They prepared bags and helped to hand them over to protesters.
Slowly, a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism has completely changed after August 9," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association, focusing on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
“I had no experience in organizing.
Everything has come.”
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the co-directors of the film, during a evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to "document" what happened.
One question came to Ferrell’s mind: “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story you can use?”
This skepticism was fuelled by countless cases of people, often whites, in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan recently explained in an interview, “We had heard that people who were born and raised in Ferguson didn’t center their voices and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist from the field known for his activism around death row inmates.
His engagement brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals, followed the team of “Who’s Streets?” in the years after Brown’s shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or speaks to us, we talk," Davis said.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people are portrayed, because that is how I will be portrayed."
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell’s experience – to show that the movement “is not a Messiah leader, but a community that comes together,” Folayan said – she proved to be the most open participant in the film.
As a result, documents from “Whose Streets?” show surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell’s life as she falls in love and marries her wife.
“I felt like naked,” Ferrell said, laughing when she first saw the finished product.
"But I understood that there must be some vulnerability in this work and the humanization of black people."
Furthermore, Ferrell’s story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who shaped the film "BlacklivesMatter" on social media after the killing of the black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012, identify as gay.
“Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement overall,” Ferrell said, “and therefore we are constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the main burden of everything.”
Folayan agreed to note that “the movement is reallyined by black women and many black women.”
However, she insists that “this is not an affirmative type of action” in which Ferrell was selected as the heart of the film due to her identity.
“She was the person who shaken up that energy,” she said.
“It’s not a coincidence, though she was at the forefront because with a life at these intersections as a black, gay woman, so much is at stake.
You can feel their energy through the screen.”
Meanwhile, the news cameras in Ferguson have long since disappeared, but the racial ties between the community and the police continue.
Ferrell is jailed for two and a half years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area, which she calls her home: “A Chaos.”
Still, she clings to a song and she feels committed to that memory since she walked out on the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose except our chains.”
