“I find it so nice to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years,” he said.
"What a personal relationship to hold this letter in my hand."
'A Castle in England' spans the period from the Middle Ages to the age of Edward and documents the families who lived in Scotney. Each story was illustrated by a different, emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It’s not Rhodes’ first book based on an archive: he wrote 2014’s ‘Dead Men’s Teeth and Other Stories’, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library – a project he unexpectedly found emotional.
"I just reacted to the thumbprint on the side of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700s who worked for the Jacobins," he says.
“This is his fingerprint.
Letters always smell smoke, because at that time a fire was lit because of the light.
For someone who lives 300 years later, the smell has an effect as if he was himself.
I love the archives!”
For someone so struck with old papers that he’s backed by the National Trust and the Arts Council England and lived in a castle for four months (“To be honest: I’ve a little overestimated my welcome greeting”) this all seems too nice to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian “new” castle, looking through the archives and studying the castle’s many treasures and curiosities, such as the mounted hyena heads on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries digging.
He walked through the site and the ruins of the old castle and spoke with landscapers, gardeners, and sometimes with the artists who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then, at night, he drank whiskey and began to write.
The intimate story of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust received full access only in 2006 when her last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the employees just started taking care of the archive, which he described as “hundreds of years in which aristocrats said, “Oh, throw it on the roof.”
Diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, maps depicting who owned what: “You might think land conflicts would be boring,” Rhodes says, “but there was a birch for which two families fought.
Boys, let it all go!”
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to immerse yourself in English history on a wider basis, including 'The Labourer', which follows a man leaving the newly built castle to join the peasant uprising of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot that occurred in 1380 at the castle, in this book titled 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex'," says Rhodes.
“The peasant uprising began in this area and I thought an uprising was a good start.
Per the two are connected?”
Other stories are firmly rooted in the history of the castle - such as 'The Priest', which tells the story of the Jesuit father whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler', which depicts the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell who staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery made only years later when his coffin was excavated).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family of Scotney: "The gentlemen seemed to be pretty scammers, constantly making debts and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying wealthy old women – I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking boys, with a talent to promote inheritance.”
After the end of his service at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness for a comic book about Elämänmäki, the site of a sanatorium from the early 20th century that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
“I was sad to go back,” he says.
It was like, “Oh, now I have to deal with the damn life again.”
