Red Meat, Milk Products, and Chocolate Could Help Relieve IBD (Inflammatory Bowel Disease)
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study claims the exact opposite: A diet rich in meat-based proteins and dairy products could relieve the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable condition, which affects around 1.3 million people in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurring or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
While those affected are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan of proteins helps develop immune cells that promote a tolerant gut.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells patrol in the gut to ensure that harmful microbes hidden in food do not enter the body.
Cells that are able to trigger inflammation are balanced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance tends too far towards inflammation, it can result in inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have found that a kind of tolerance-promoting immune cell occurs in mice that carry a specific bacterium in their intestines.
And the bacterium needs tryptophan – one of the building blocks of proteins – to trigger the appearance of the cells.
Professor Colonna said, “We have made a connection between a species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a normal part of the gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would promote a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment, if the same system also works in humans.
Postdoctoral student Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan studied a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that one group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same strain, which was housed separately, did not.
She suspected that the difference had to do with the intestinal microbiome of mice – the community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of the mice were DNA sequenced and six species of bacteria were found that were present in the mice with the immune cells, but were absent in the mice.
Mice were raised in a sterile environment so they lacked an intestinal microbiome and they did not develop this type of immune cells, and they received the L. reuteri and the immune cells were created.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers allowed L. reuteri to grow in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid – without the bacteria – to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells evolved into tolerance-promoting cells.
When the active component was cleared from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, known as indol-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the feed of the mice, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and that most of us protect L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri develop cells in humans as in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said, “The development of these cells is probably something we want to promote as these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the gut.
Potentially, high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can lead to an expansion of this population."
