White House advertising costs taxpayers thousands
The White House’s decision to fly a naval helicopter to South Lawn for an event highlighting U.S. manufacturing last month costs taxpayers up to $24,000, according to military data left to TIME magazine.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One, when the President is on board, was the heart of the event on July 17 at the White House with American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials took a tour of products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was exhibited alongside a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire car, and a Mississippi funnel.
The White House military office demanded the presence of the helicopter in a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I just wanted you to be aware of this because it's such an unusual event with high visibility," the commander of the HMX-1 wrote on the eve of the event to his superior, the Navy's deputy commander of aviation.
The news indicated that the helicopter arrived at the South Lawn for the event at 15 a.m. on July 17, and stayed there until the lawn was cleared between 18:00 and 21:00 that evening.
The note adds that if the departure from the White House was delayed, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to the restriction of hours of service.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event, while the unit’s security personnel remained on the ground with the aircraft during the time.
The records made available to TIME did not make it clear whether a second flight crew was ultimately needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 has asked if the event could violate the fate.
"One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that this was not the case," the commander wrote.
“It sounds like you’re locked up,” the deputy commander replied.
The "Made in America" event was designated by the White House as an official event and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave a boost to the healthcare reform reform that was ongoing in the Senate, and he propagated efforts to curb government regulations.
The use of the aircraft, known as Marine One or Air Force One, for politically beneficial purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are obliged to use them for the trip.
But asking for their use only for a photo-OP is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane was providing taxi services against the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of reports complaining about its predecessor’s use of the presidential plane.
“The White House is enthusiastic about the ‘Made in America’ show – showing products from all 50 states made by American workers with American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, the White House’s deputy press secretary.
HMX-1 crews frequently perform training flights in the area around Washington and South Lawn to take down the U.S. president at the White House with precise centimeters.
