The flight for the "Made in America" event included in the flight crew training needs for the month, a official said.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for “non-presidential support missions.”
The White House said taxpayers took on the burden for none of the other requests presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in displaying the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records for the presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to the U.S. Department of Defense’s hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the DoD reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records record the flight time of the aircraft as 30 minutes from the home base of the Marine Corps Air Facility in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is well below that rate.
"Setting the cost for taxpayers based on estimates for the refund rates is highly misleading," Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs included in the annual funding.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, the reimbursement rates for DoD do not include personnel costs, but take into account costs for fuel, maintenance and contract conclusion.
At that time, former White House spokesman Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the event.
