Afghan democracy depends on women’s political role, says UN
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, play a role, the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, current head of the United Nations mission, said hundreds of women will run for the council elections in the provinces. Three women are running for the role of vice president and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
“The role of women cannot be overestimated,” he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women are fully involved and involved in all aspects of the electoral process.
Afghan elections for the provincial council and the presidential elections will be held on April 5.
The Taliban has issued threats against an election process that coincides with the transition from international combat operations to a consultative role.
This year, for the first time, elections will pass power peacefully from one democratically elected government to the next.
Haysom said a strong role for women will further strengthen Afghanistan’s democratic success.
The Afghan Independent Electoral Commission reports that 1.2 million women are registered among the total of 3.6 million registered voters.
