GMB concerns about investment in McVitie factory in Glasgow
A trade union wants to assure managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitie of the long-term commitment to production at their factory in Glasgow.
GMB Scotland said the company has been silent about the future of investment at Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work in the factory, which, among other products, makes Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies.
McVities owner Pladis said he has invested more than £5 million over the past few years.
He added that employees and trade union representatives would be “first to know” if their activities were to change.
In a letter to the company’s branch manager, GMB urged Scotland McVitie’s to “express concerns that funding for the modernization of production lines will not be advanced.”
GMB Senior Organizer Drew Duffy said: “The fact that we can’t get clarity from the general site manager about the business needs and investment plans for Tollcross’ future is deeply affecting our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily focused on the local community and the large area of Glasgow, an important pillar for decent employment in an area with high unemployment and social disadvantages.
Therefore, in the perspective of jobs, wages and prosperity, and in the context of Brexit, rising cost of living and chronic decline in production, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a thriving production presence at McVitie.”
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: “Tollcross’s branch manager just received a letter from GMB Scotland yesterday, and the company will respond directly to it as we appreciate the continued engagement of employees and trade union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with employees and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, where some issues were openly discussed.
We discussed with employees that, like all companies operating in an extremely competitive and uncertain economic environment, we are constantly reviewing our – and this applies to all our business branches and locations – in order to remain competitive.
She added: “Over the past few years, we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross site, in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognize the legacy of Tollcross as a production facility.If our operating processes at the site change, the employees and their trade union representatives will be the first to know about this."
Did Barcelona warn Neymar three years ago?
The La Liga side may regret their interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain won’t go down in her pursuit of Neymar after making an offer of £189 million to trigger his release clause, but did they warn Barcelona three years ago of the world record robbery?
The sensational approach has fueled the transfer window this summer as the Ligue 1 club is ready to break the world record by more than twice the previous mark, with Paul Pogba returning to Manchester United last season for £89 million.
After termination, Neymar becomes the most expensive player in the world and the highest paid professional athlete in the world. PSG offers salaries of more than £500,000 per week.
Barcelona is angry at the way Neymar has forced his way out, although a source close to the Catalan board insists that the club has always done its best to take care of him since he arrived from Santos in 2013.
But was the football world warned three years ago by the PSG president about this prospect?
When Manchester City expressed interest in signing Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi had a strict warning to any club that wanted one of PSG’s best players to sign.
"I'm not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we'll stand in opposition to them, we'll contact their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
“We respect all clubs.
But if they try to get one of our players to sign with them, it will have consequences.”
Barcelona seems to have crossed that line, with the Spanish club expressing interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG made it clear that they would not allow the international from Italy to leave under any circumstances, and Barcelona could feel the consequences of that interest by losing one of their prize offers for Neymar.
