Interview: "Domspatzen report relieves pope-brother Georg Ratzinger"
The Regensburg Domspatzen report on the abuse cases relieves Pope-Brother Georg Ratzinger.
This is stated by the author and historian Michael Hesemann.
The final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburger Domspatzen continues to cause discussion.
Christian Weisnder, spokesman for the reform movement "We are the Church", said after the publication to the German press agency that he expects an apology from the former Bishop of Regensburg and present-day Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller as well as from the cathedral master Georg Ratzinger, the 93-year-old brother of the emeritus Pope Benedict XVI.
It would be of great service to the reputation of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger expressed their deep regret for their own omissions or their wrong assessment of the events at the time.
The Vatican newspaper Osservatore Romano, on the other hand, criticized the use of "two measures" in reporting violence among the catholics.
Regarding the attacks in Regensburg, no one doubts that they are "shameful and shameful acts" that need to be punished and prevented in the future; but the "degree of media manipulation" is striking, says author Lucetta Scaraffia, historian and member of the Italian National Bioethics Committee.
“The habit of referring to the Catholic Church as the source of all evil is already part of everyday experience and prepares the public opinion to consider it normal,” Scaraffia writes.
Also Princess Gloria of Thurn and Taxis said in an interview with the Bavarian broadcaster: "You like to go to church and that is a found meal."
In addition, she pointed out that in her youth, “strikes were a normal educational means” to “to deal with frightening children like I was one.”
It would be unfair to apply today’s standards to previous decades, because the world has changed.
In connection with the reports of the abuse cases, the pope-brother Georg Ratzinger also appeared frequently.
Completely wrong, writer and historian Michael Hesemann, who wrote with Ratzinger the memoir "My Brother the Pope" (translated into 12 languages).
"I have to take Georg Ratzinger in protection," says Hesemann, "because all this had nothing to do with him," he evaluates the results of the final report.
What exactly is stated in the 440-page report presented by Ulrich Weber, a lawyer commissioned by the Bishop of Regensburg for the enlightenment?
A total of 547 Regensburger Domspatzen were sexually abused between 1945 and the early 1990s with "high plausibility" victims of assaults.
Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994, said in the final report: "In summary, it can be concluded that Domkapellmeister R. in many cases used forms of physical and psychological violence.
Especially with high emotionality, the punishment for the students could also be harsher.
Nevertheless, unlike many other accused, it is evident that many victims appreciated R.’s general humanity and therefore, in many cases, despite violence, even associate positive memories with him.”
In the interview, Hesemann explains why, in his opinion, the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburger Domspatzen relieves Georg Ratzinger.
Mr. Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "incidents of violence against protection officers at the Regensburger Domspatzen" gives a contradictory picture of Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger.
On the one hand, many students highlight their “humanity.”
On the other hand, he also appears as a cholerist and perfectionist, who often became hands-on when a cathedral was not musically top performance.
How do you view this final biography?
Michael Hesemann: If you make the effort and read the entire 440-page report from front to back, you must rather wonder why the name Georg Ratzinger appears in it.
Only eight pages are dedicated to him and he is clearly released from any suspicion of complicity or co-consciousness in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The violence in the preschool also occurred outside its sphere of influence.
In any case, you can accuse him of learning too late or of not taking the first hints seriously enough.
The Domspatz Gymnasium, where he worked, was perceived by virtually all respondents as - so literally - "salvation", "heaven" and "better world".
Thus, the vast majority of his students, Georg Ratzinger, give a very excellent testimony, describing him as “warmhearted”, “popular”, “honest”, “competent” and “comprehensible”, as an extremely kind teacher, who regularly supplied the boys with cakes, cookies and candy and was “always packed with children’s grapes.”
Only a minority complain about his perfectionism and high emotionality, which has already led to outbreaks of anger.
That he not only knocked with chairs and threw the keyband on the floor, but also distributed earrings and pulled too ugly guys to the hair or ears, he himself has already admitted years ago, deeply regretted and apologized for it.
To his honor, however, it must be said that such educational methods were widespread in the time in question, in the 1960s and 1970s, both among parents and teachers.
Do you know about such punishment methods?
Of course, I think of every one of us who was born before 1968.
I also experienced this at a secular school, a state high school.
Compared to what is actually being discussed in this report, namely the horrible sexual abuse and the excesses of violence in preschool, these are obviously minorities.
The question is whether it is not more related to his fame and his role as the brother of Benedict XVI that many media outlets have just rushed to him.
Many of the Bavarian popes, who never understood him, are still working hard on him.
But the truth is: the report relieves Georg Ratzinger in every way!
In the media, a lot was in connection with the report on the topic of abuse in the Regensburger Domspatzen.
Is Georg Ratzinger also accused of any involvement or complicity in sexual abuse in the final report?
Michael Hesemann: Clearly not.
None of the 67 victims of sexual assault claimed to have entrusted themselves to the cathedral master.
Not even the parents were invited.
"I never dared to talk to my father or my mother about it," one affected person told the other, "I was very embarrassed."
The real problem with educating about sexual abuse was, and is, that most victims remain silent out of shame.
If they did not even trust their parents and siblings, then not a choir leader, who would have been professionally a colleague of the perpetrators.
How do the Domspatzen students assess Ratzinger’s role in the case of abuse?
Michael Hesemann: A student interviewed stated: “In terms of sexual abuse ... I see ... no case in which he (Georg Ratzinger) would have had timely findings and could have stopped the perpetrator.
I find it ... also really absurd to assume that just him ... boys have opened up more intrusively or clearly than to their parents, internat leaders, trust teachers, etc.
Talking to him about sex is unthinkable.”
Thus, the report comes to the very clear conclusion: "The fact that the students concerned in advance and/or their surroundings were entrusted to him could not be confirmed in the context of the investigation."
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger is therefore to be released from any co-consciousness.
Nor can he be accused of not preventing him or bringing him to notice.
Therefore, there is also no reason to associate his good name with these disgusting crimes, as unfortunately happened in some cases.
In the media, a lot of "violent excesses" were read at the Regensburger Domspatzen.
Former cathedral master Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report "Wegschauen".
Should he live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: This is the big problem, that in the reporting everything was mixed and mixed into a huge mixture of sexual abuse and violent excesses and somewhere, in the middle, Georg Ratzinger.
However, this is an abuse of the report.
There is a clear separation: between preschool and high school, between sexual abuse and excesses of violence, and, let’s say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the time since 1945, i.e. also from four decades when Georg Ratzinger was not the choir leader of the Domspatzen.
All the terrible punishment pedagogy, the cases in which boys were really harassed and abused by sadistic teachers and suffered terribly, all occurred in the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where really scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But with them the cathedral master Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do, because he only got the boys to face when they were already at the cathedral gymnasium.
On it, as the vast majority of witnesses emphasize, the topic of "pre-school" was taboo.
One was just lucky to have escaped her and the so much better treatment and for many even "paradise" states.
What was different at the High School?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but not sadistic violence.
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger, where the report concludes that "many victims appreciated R.'s general humanity and therefore in numerous cases, despite violence, even associate positive memories with him."
At the very least, the accusation remains to have looked away.
However, despite all efforts, the report was able to define only two periods during which it was about the conditions in preschool.
The first time in 1970/71, when he had just begun to establish himself, and about the events at a school where he just did not act and was responsible, (so the witness) did not want to hear anything, and then again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears before the circumstances?
Michael Hesemann: No, because in 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
In it, he points out that "the punishment for punishment is still practiced in preschool."
Even given the danger of negative press releases, he urged urgent intervention.
This was, of course, at a time when legal clarity existed, when punishment for punishment was already banned in Bavaria.
Before, they happened in a legal gray zone, as we all know.
It was also difficult for him to estimate where the affected may have exaggerated or dramatized and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
You can’t say that he has always looked away.
That is simply not true.
It was only in 1980 that the punishment for bullying in schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria of Thurn and Taxis argued that it was unfair to apply the pedagogical standards of today to the time.
How do you see it?
Michael Hesemann: We historians are talking about the “fall of anachronism,” that is, the danger of judging the past according to today’s moral standards.
The princess is right.
But, of course, this does not apply to sexual abuse, which was disgusting at all times, nor to what was broken in preschool with disgust and violence against innocent children’s souls, which goes far beyond the usual at the time.
This is all terrible and I am glad that it is finally being worked out.
But at the same time I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because all this had nothing to do with him.
His means of discipline and punishment, i.e. pulling ears and hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When physical punishment was then prohibited, he also strictly adhered to it.
What image of his time in Regensburg did Georg Ratzinger reflect in the conversations with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Was the issue of punishment also discussed?
Michael Hesemann: Well, in the book it is about the life of his brother Joseph, that is, Pope Benedict XVI, told from his perspective, the cathedrals played only a secondary role.
Nevertheless, I did not hide that he was leading a strict regiment there.
But this too must be said: Without this perfectionism, without the requirement of unconditional discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to form a world-class institution from the until then more nationally known Regensburg cathedrals, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition, who went on tour in the United States twice (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With cookies and candy alone, you do not make rebellious boys great singers and before every success, no matter in what field, but always discipline, passion and self-conquerance.
What kind of person did you experience Georg Ratzinger in the conversations about your book?
Michael Hesemann: Through the work on the book and beyond, I really met Georg Ratzinger very well and repeatedly experienced him as a wonderful, humorous, basic, deeply believing and good-hearted person, of whom one cannot imagine that he could hurt even a fly.
I regularly get to know how many ex-dom spats still today, 23 years after his retirement, keep regular contact with him, visit him, read to him – he is almost blind – and treat him like a member of their family.
Those who did not forgive him to this day that he was once strict with them are therefore clearly in the minority.
Most cathedrals today are grateful to him for enriching their lives and bringing them closer to the world of music.
And that he was always a good, paternal teacher – a strict father, of course, that may be – but yet he was also a lovable respectful person, to whom they still look up today and whom they just adore.
And please, again very clearly: all that is blamed on him are educational methods that were on the agenda at the time.
We can be happy that we have overcome this time long ago.
But it is highly unfair to make a man, just because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother, a medial sin-bock.
The evil intention behind it is just too obvious.
Because the report that has just been published relieves him.
Now the decency would rule to finally leave a 93-year-old man who has earned great merits and without those outside Bavaria and even Germany nobody would know the Regensburger Domspatzen in peace.
